{{Infobox military person | honorific_prefix = | name = Moriyama Einosuke | honorific_suffix = | image = Moriyama Einosuke (left) 森山 栄之助.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Moriyama Einosuke (left) | native_name = 森山 栄之助 | native_name_lang = ja | birth_name = | other_name = | nickname = | birth_date = {{birth date|1820|07|10}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|1872|05|04|1820|07|10}} | death_place = | placeofburial_label = | placeofburial = | placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | allegiance = | branch = | serviceyears = | serviceyears_label = | rank = | rank_label = | servicenumber = <!-- Do not use data from primary sources such as service records --> | unit = | commands = | battles_label = | battles = | awards = | memorials = | spouse = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced --> | relations = | laterwork = Interpreter | signature = | signature_size = | signature_alt = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | module = }}
{{Japanese name|Moriyama}}
{{nihongo|'''Moriyama Einosuke'''|森山 栄之助||extra=July 10, 1820 – May 4, 1872}} was a [[samurai]] during the [[Tokugawa shogunate]], and an interpreter of Dutch and English. He studied English under Dutch merchants and [[Ranald MacDonald]]. He was called upon to assist shogunate officials during the "Manhattan Incident" of 1845, during which the American whaling ship [[Manhattan (1843 ship)|''Manhattan'']] approached [[Edo]] to repatriate 22 castaway Japanese seamen. <ref name="Van Zandt">{{cite book|last=Van Zandt|first=Howard|title=Pioneer American Merchants in Japan|year=1984|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=9994648144|page=68-72}}</ref> As Chief Dutch Interpreter, he was later one of the chief men involved in the negotiations with [[Matthew Calbraith Perry|Commodore Perry]] in regard to the [[sakoku|opening of Japan]] to the outside world.
[[Samuel Wells Williams]], a member of Perry's second visit noted in 1854: {{cquote|A new and superior interpreter came with Saborosuke, named Moriyama Yenosuke&nbsp;... He speaks English well enough to render any other interpreter unnecessary, and this will assist our intercourse greatly. He&nbsp;... asked if Ronald McDonald (sic) was well, or if we knew him.&nbsp;... giving us all a good impression of his education and breeding. (Williams, p.120, March 3rd 1854)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AeY8AAAAIAAJ&q=%22A+new+and+superior+interpreter+came%22&dq=%22A+new+and+superior+interpreter+came%22&as_brr=0&hl=en ''Sōritsu nijisshūnen kinen ronshū'']</ref><ref>''Treaties and other international acts of the United States of America'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=ofMOAAAAYAAJ&q=%22A+new+and+superior+interpreter+came%22&dq=%22A+new+and+superior+interpreter+came%22&as_brr=0&hl=en]</ref><ref>''Native American in the land of the shogun'' by Frederik L. Schodt p.288 [https://books.google.com/books?id=lIk0eweZVfEC&pg=PA288]</ref>}}
